# Parametric Surfaces

<div class="block">

![Revolution Diagram](/img/diagrams/calculus/surface-of-revolution-parametric.png)

To form a surface of revolution (not necessarily to compute its surface area), we can consider a parametric system of
two variables. For instance, consider the surface $S$ obtained by rotating the curve $y = f(x)$, $a \leq x \leq b$,
about the $x$-axis (other axes handled similarly), where $f(x) \geq 0$. Let $\theta$ be the angle of rotation formed
by some point $P(x, y, z)$ on $f(x)$ and the $xy$-plane. Then
$$ x = x, \quad y = f(x)\cos{\theta}, \quad z = f(x)\sin{\theta}. $$
Therefore, we can take $x$ and $\theta$ as the parameters and regard the above as the parametric equations of $S$
where the parameter domain is given by $a \leq x \leq b$, $0 \leq \theta \leq 2\pi$.

